Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains infoirmation about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. The dataset contains 21 features such as popularity, budget, revenue, genre, release year, and runtime. In addition to other features that will not used in the analysis.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

1-First question I will be addressing in this analysis is the relation between the budget of a movie and its revenue, where the budget of the movie will be the independent variable and revenue the dependent variable.

2-Second question for analysis is, what are the most popular genre through the years from 1960 to 2015.

#first, I will define a function to plot a histogram for the variables more easily
def plot_func(data, title, label, color):
    sns.set_theme()
    plt.figure(figsize= (10,10))
    plt.title(str(title), fontsize = 18)
    plt.hist(data, bins = 35, label=str(label), color = str(color))
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.show()
    sns.set_theme()
    plt.figure(figsize= (10,10))
    plt.title(str(title)+ ' (log)', fontsize = 18)
    plt.hist(data, bins = 35, label=str(label), color = str(color))
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.show()

df1 = df.assign(genres=df.genres.str.split('|')).explode('genres').reset_index()
In [127]:
#dropping the old index column
df1.drop(columns='index',inplace=True)
In [128]:
#creating a numpy array of the years 
year_lst=np.sort(np.array(df['release_year'].unique()))
In [129]:
#grouping by year and genre to get the mean for each genre in each year
df2=df1.groupby(['release_year','genres'])
In [130]:
#creating arrays for year, genre, and popularity to append to a new dataframe
lst=np.array(df2.groups.keys())
genres=np.empty(0,str)
year=np.empty(0,int)
popularity=np.empty(0)
for key in lst.item():
    popularity=np.append(popularity,df2.get_group(key)['popularity'].mean())
    genres=np.append(genres,key[1])
    year=np.append(year,key[0])
In [131]:
df_m = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(year,genres,popularity)), columns =['release_year','genres','popularity'])
In [132]:
df_m.duplicated().sum()
Out[132]:
0

Now, that I have created a dataframe with the mean popularity for each genre in each year with no duplicates, I can query to get the genre with maximum mean popularity in each year.

In [133]:
#running a query for each year to get the genre with max popularity and appending the result to a new dataframe d_n
df_n=pd.DataFrame()
for year in year_lst:
    df_year=df_m.query('release_year=={}'.format(year))
    df_q=df_year.query('popularity=={}'.format(df_year.popularity.max()))
    df_n=pd.concat([df_n,df_q],ignore_index=True)

Conclusions¶

The variables I investigated in this analysis were budget, revenue, genres, and release year. The focused research area was to study the relationship between the budget of a movie, and its revenue using the appropriate graphs, and confirming the correlation between data with the appropriate statistical tests. Moreover, acquiring the most popular movie genre (that is, the genre with the highest mean popularity score) throughout all years in the data.

The Correlation between a Movie's Revenue and its Budget¶

From the regression line plotted atop the scatterplot, there appears to be a positive correlation between a movie's budget and its revenue. Confirming the positive correlation between the budget and revenue requires using a statistical test. The appropriate tests to be used are Pearson's test and Spearman's test. Due to the data being non-normally distributed, I used Spearman's correlation test.

$$\text{Spearman's correlation coefficient: }H_0 = 0.707583$$$$\text{With p-value: }p = 0$$

The correlation coefficient indicates a strong positive correlation between the data. The zero p-value indicates that there is a 0% possibility that the data can be correlated randomly (a false positive). Hence, the results are statistically significant.

With the following regression line equation: $$revenue = -854933 + 2.78168\times budget$$

The Most Popular Genre across all Years¶

For this analysis, I managed to determine the genre with the highest mean popularity score for each year in the dataset. And I made a graphical representation of the result in this table.

Furthermore, I determined the most popular and least popular genres on average in this graph.

  • Adventure was the most popular genre on average with a popularity score of 1.154259.
  • Documentary was the least popular genre on avergae with a popularity score of 0.181432.

Additional Research Areas¶

Many different research areas may be explored in this dataset, such as:

  • The relation between movie runtime and release year
  • the relation between movie runtime and revenue
  • the relation between popularity and budget

Limitations¶

The correlation coefficient of the linear regression is the Pearson correlation coefficient equal to 0.734851131007624, which is useful in normally distributed data. However, this is not the case here as the data is left-skewed. Also, the result of the linear regression returns a linear relationship between the data, which may not be necessarily the case.

The variation in budget is not sufficient to determine the financial success of a movie, as other factors need to be considered such as the cast and crew, runtime, and genre.

Finally, it is worth noting that getting the most popular genre per year may not be the most useful gauge in this particular situation, as each movie is categorized in different genres. Hence, the genres present in the most popular movies will rise to the top even if it is not the main genre of the film.
